# Graph Basics in Java

A graph is just a collection of **nodes (vertices)** connected by **edges**. Unlike a tree, edges can point anywhere — there is no root, no parent-child direction requirement, and cycles are allowed. Think of a city road map: intersections are nodes, roads are edges. Your job with most graph problems is to move through that map systematically without getting lost or going in circles.

## Representations — adjacency list vs adjacency matrix
```java
// ADJACENCY LIST — standard choice for sparse graphs
// Space: O(V + E)   Edge lookup: O(degree)
//
//  Graph:  0──1──2
//          |     |
//          3─────┘
//
List<List<Integer>> adj = new ArrayList<>();
for (int i = 0; i < 4; i++) adj.add(new ArrayList<>());
adj.get(0).add(1); adj.get(1).add(0);  // undirected: add both directions
adj.get(1).add(2); adj.get(2).add(1);
adj.get(2).add(3); adj.get(3).add(2);
adj.get(0).add(3); adj.get(3).add(0);

// ADJACENCY MATRIX — good for dense graphs or when edge lookup must be O(1)
// Space: O(V²)
int[][] matrix = new int[4][4];
matrix[0][1] = matrix[1][0] = 1;  // undirected edge 0-1
```

## BFS — explore level by level, like ripples in a pond
```java
// BFS gives you the SHORTEST PATH in hops (unweighted graphs).
// Picture: drop a stone in water — the ripple front expands one ring at a time.
// Nodes on ring k are all exactly k hops from the source.
//
int[] bfs(List<List<Integer>> adj, int src, int n) {
    int[] dist = new int[n];
    Arrays.fill(dist, -1);
    dist[src] = 0;
    Queue<Integer> q = new ArrayDeque<>();
    q.offer(src);
    while (!q.isEmpty()) {
        int u = q.poll();
        for (int v : adj.get(u)) {
            if (dist[v] == -1) {     // not yet visited
                dist[v] = dist[u] + 1;
                q.offer(v);
            }
        }
    }
    return dist;  // dist[v] = shortest hops from src to v
}
```

## DFS — dive deep first, backtrack when stuck
```java
// DFS explores one branch as far as possible before trying another.
// Picture: navigating a maze — you go straight until a dead end,
// then backtrack to the last junction and try a different turn.
//
// Recursive DFS
void dfs(List<List<Integer>> adj, boolean[] visited, int u) {
    visited[u] = true;
    for (int v : adj.get(u)) {
        if (!visited[v]) dfs(adj, visited, v);
    }
}

// Iterative DFS (explicit stack — same effect, avoids stack overflow on huge graphs)
void dfsIterative(List<List<Integer>> adj, int src, int n) {
    boolean[] visited = new boolean[n];
    Deque<Integer> stack = new ArrayDeque<>();
    stack.push(src);
    while (!stack.isEmpty()) {
        int u = stack.pop();
        if (visited[u]) continue;
        visited[u] = true;
        for (int v : adj.get(u)) if (!visited[v]) stack.push(v);
    }
}
```

## Connected components — run BFS/DFS from every unvisited node
```java
// Each call to dfs() from an unvisited node discovers one full component.
// Like flood-fill: colour one island, then find the next uncoloured cell.
int countComponents(List<List<Integer>> adj, int n) {
    boolean[] visited = new boolean[n];
    int components = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        if (!visited[i]) {
            dfs(adj, visited, i);  // marks entire component
            components++;
        }
    }
    return components;
}
```

## Cycle detection — undirected vs directed
```java
// UNDIRECTED: during DFS, if you reach a visited node that is NOT your parent → cycle
boolean hasCycleUndirected(List<List<Integer>> adj, int u, int parent, boolean[] vis) {
    vis[u] = true;
    for (int v : adj.get(u)) {
        if (!vis[v]) { if (hasCycleUndirected(adj, v, u, vis)) return true; }
        else if (v != parent) return true;  // visited & not parent → back edge → cycle
    }
    return false;
}

// DIRECTED: use 3-state coloring
// WHITE(0) = unvisited, GRAY(1) = in current DFS path, BLACK(2) = fully processed
// Back edge (white→gray) means cycle
boolean hasCycleDirected(List<List<Integer>> adj, int u, int[] color) {
    color[u] = 1;  // GRAY — currently exploring
    for (int v : adj.get(u)) {
        if (color[v] == 1) return true;       // back edge → cycle
        if (color[v] == 0 && hasCycleDirected(adj, v, color)) return true;
    }
    color[u] = 2;  // BLACK — done
    return false;
}
```

## Common Pitfalls
- Forgetting to mark a node visited BEFORE enqueuing (BFS) — causes duplicate processing
- Undirected graph: not adding edges in BOTH directions when building adjacency list
- Cycle detection: in undirected graphs, the parent node looks like a back-edge — must track parent to avoid false positive
- Using adjacency matrix for very sparse graphs — wastes O(V²) space
- Directed vs undirected cycle detection: they need different algorithms (back-edge check vs 3-colour DFS)

## Connections
- **Queues**: BFS is level-order traversal using a queue
- **Recursion/Stacks**: DFS uses the call stack (or an explicit stack)
- **Trees**: a tree is a special graph (connected, acyclic) — tree algorithms are graph algorithms in disguise
- **Heaps**: Dijkstra replaces the BFS queue with a min-heap for weighted shortest paths
